transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thanks for calling Viagra, Quinn speaking, how can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yeah, I need to cancel my prescription for Viagra, and I had the idea that it was a reoccurring charge.

Speaker 1: Yeah, it's not. It doesn't have to be, sir. It's totally up to you. Let me pull up your account.

Speaker 2: No, I know, but you've got options.

Speaker 1: No, we don't choose it either way, sir. We just provide the options for you to choose, and if you don't, then it will go out.

Speaker 2: You know how the doctor writes it, but it's totally up to you, as I say, that you can choose how you want it to come out.

Speaker 1: Well, I want to cancel it completely.

Speaker 2: Okay, so you don't want to order as needed?

Speaker 1: No.

Speaker 2: You know what I mean? That would be, you know, you would order when you call in for your orders.

Speaker 1: That's when you would receive anything.

Speaker 2: Sir, I don't want to receive them anymore. I want to cancel my prescription.

Speaker 1: Any particular reason why?

Speaker 2: Yeah, I don't want it. You know, Viagra, it just doesn't make me feel right. I get headaches.

Speaker 1: Well, yeah, if it's giving you headaches. I mean, this medication is really subject to body chemistry, and we do have other Viagras.

Speaker 2: Now, now, listen to me.

Speaker 1: Sir, sir, stop. I just want to cancel.

Speaker 2: Can you listen to me? I heard you the first time. I'm just doing my job.

Speaker 1: Well, then cancel my order.

Speaker 2: I can help you, okay? So calm down and let me talk. I wasn't talking over you. I let you talk.

Speaker 1: I know you want to cancel. I hear you loud and clear.

Speaker 2: Probably how you ended up getting this the second time anyway.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I don't want it.
